To find the union of sets A and B (A ∪ B), we combine all the elements from both sets, without repeating any elements. 

A = {1, 2, 3}
B = {3, 4, 5}

A ∪ B = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}

Now, we need to determine whether A and B are both subsets of A ∪ B.

A subset is a set where all its elements are also elements of another set. In this case, we can see that all elements of A and B are present in A ∪ B:

A = {1, 2, 3} is a subset of A ∪ B = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}
B = {3, 4, 5} is a subset of A ∪ B = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}

Therefore, A and B are both subsets of A ∪ B.
